{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17644326","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17644326"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T20:04:09+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T20:04:09+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18039"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18039","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18039"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.05,0.55,0.09,0.23,0.09]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10753"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74139"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10753","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10753"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18039"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"59630"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4946"},{"type":"tags","id":"8407"},{"type":"tags","id":"10204"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"25086"},{"type":"contributions","id":"25091"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74139","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/74139"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the function of the Haversian canals in bone?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Store calcium and phosphate","Provide a pathway for blood vessels and nerves","Facilitate bone growth and repair","Connect adjacent osteocytes","Act as a reservoir for bone marrow"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003EHaversian canals\u003C/strong\u003E are integral components of the Haversian system, or osteon, which is the fundamental functional unit of compact bone. These canals run longitudinally through the bone and provide a pathway for blood vessels and nerves, ensuring that bone tissue receives the necessary nutrients and can remove waste products efficiently.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhile \u003Cstrong\u003Estoring calcium and phosphate\u003C/strong\u003E is a critical function of bone, it is not the primary role of the Haversian canals. Instead, this storage occurs in the bone matrix.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFacilitating bone growth and repair\u003C/strong\u003E involves various cells and processes, including osteoblasts and osteoclasts, but the Haversian canals themselves do not directly contribute to these processes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Ereservoir for bone marrow\u003C/strong\u003E is found in the medullary cavity of long bones, not within the Haversian canals.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhile the Haversian system includes connections between osteocytes through canaliculi, the primary role of the Haversian canals is not to \u003Cstrong\u003Econnect adjacent osteocytes\u003C/strong\u003E but to house blood vessels and nerves.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The Haversian canals are part of the bone\u0027s microstructure, providing a pathway for blood vessels and nerves.","The Haversian system, or osteon, is the fundamental functional unit of compact bone.","The arrangement of Haversian canals allows for efficient nutrient and waste exchange in bone tissue."],"references":["Gartner, L. P. (2020). Textbook of histology e-book: Textbook of histology e-book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Baig MA, Bacha D. Histology, Bone. 2023 May 1. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 31082176","Blumer MJF. Bone tissue and histological and molecular events during development of the long bones. Ann Anat. 2021 May;235:151704. doi: 10.1016/j.aanat.2021.151704. Epub 2021 Feb 16. PMID: 33600952","Florencio-Silva R, Sasso GR, Sasso-Cerri E, Sim\u00f5es MJ, Cerri PS. Biology of Bone Tissue: Structure, Function, and Factors That Influence Bone Cells. Biomed Res Int. 2015;2015:421746. doi: 10.1155/2015/421746. Epub 2015 Jul 13. PMID: 26247020; PMCID: PMC4515490"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"59630"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18039"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"59630","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/59630"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-24T21:31:42+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-24T22:08:22+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10753"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74139"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}